Linda Smith Clark
September 11 at 8:53 AM ·

Hello friends! I’m excited to announce that on Saturday September 12th, three releases from Potter’s piano and violin project will be featured on WSKG Classical Radio (Binghamton 91.5, Corning 90.7, Greene 88.1, Ithaca 92.1, Cooperstown 105.9). The host of “Play It Again, Sam” has offered to air pieces, composed by Potter, after the NPR news updates at 2pm, 3pm, and 4pm, and follow them up with some short words on the pieces as well as the performers (Carson Boches, Bryce Clearing-Sky, and Potter). I hope you’ll tune in to hear the latest contemporary classical music in the area, and support a great local radio show. You can also stream the show live or after the fact on WSKG’s website!

post_text:
A pandemic can bring out plenty of creativity as is indicated by the new, vinyl Tiger Paws designed and created by UEHS tech teachers Tom Palazzo. Corey Munn, and Mike Wichowski.
Using software and a vinyl printer, over 250 round Tiger Paws were created. These paws were laid down in the elementary buildings, six feet apart in areas such as the cafeteria and main lobby. These paws serve as reminders to social distance, helping to keep our students and staff safe and following the state guidelines.
Thank you for all your work on creating the Tiger Paws!

post_text:
Kindergarten Jumpstart kicked-off this week as our newest Tiger Cubs visited their elementary schools. As in years past, students toured the building, and met teachers and other staff.
Students worked briefly with teachers on letters and numbers, went through the cafeteria, saw the playground, went to the gym, and got their new Chromebooks as part of the 1:1 technology initiative.

There were some obvious differences this year. Instead of four days on site – students/families had an appointment for one a morning during the week.

Students also learned about using hand sanitizers, walking in the halls along the new tiger paws that are spaced six feet apart, and how the virtual days will work, which included meeting teachers via their Chromebooks.

Thank you to all the staff who helped make Kindergarten Jumpstart a success!

post_text:
Even during a pandemic, our UEHS Tigers find a way to make volunteering a priority.
Over the last two months, incoming seniors Abigail Winans, Emily Amlin, Kinaed Forsyth, and 2019 graduate Toby Gusefski volunteered at Broome County Habitat with fundraisers and other special events.
Recently, Habitat had a special need for extra hands at a construction site. Normally, construction is usually reserved for those who are 18 years or older. When an early morning call came in, these students answered and headed to the job site.
They helped pour the concrete footer that needed to get done so the project could stay on schedule. Thank you to these students for the extra set of hands. It could not have been completed on time without their help! #TigerPride

Community and collaboration continue to be at the forefront of the upcoming school year. And that includes generous donations from members of our school community.
When Josh and Megan Brown, U-E parents with students in the eighth- and first-grades, heard that the district was providing at-home supplies to students they wanted to contribute.
Megan said, “When we saw that, we decided we wanted to buy supplies to help out.” Megan delivered nearly a dozen bags full of binders, notebooks, and many other supplies for students in grades K-8.
Thank you to the Browns! Together we are #TigerPride #TigerStrong.

post_text:
UEHS graduate Scott Sasina (Class of 2010) was recently promoted from morning news anchor to evening news anchor at local CBS affiliate WBNG-TV.
Along with new responsibilities, he also had new promotional photos taken. He decided the best place to take those photos was at UEHS Ty Cobb Stadium. He chose the stadium because he takes great pride in being from U-E and wants everyone to know that not only is he representing the Greater Binghamton area when he is on-air but especially Endicott. He added, “I have so many fond memories of playing sports in this stadium and it is iconic to the area. U-E helped shape me into the man I am today and was such a big part of my life growing up. Once a Tiger, always a Tiger! #TigerPride!”
Thank you for thinking of our facilities for your professional photoshoot and for your continued support of Tiger Pride.

post_text: Bryan Tran, UEHS Class of 2017 graduate, was recently selected as an ACTFL Scholar through the Center for Assessment, Research and Development. ACTFL (American Council on the Teaching of Foreign Languages) is a nationally recognized organization that provides language educators with innovation, vision, and leadership in the teaching of foreign languages. This summer, Bryan is conducting research on how integrating social media into the world language classroom can influence interpersonal, interpretive, and presentational communication. In addition, he will be gathering resources for language teachers to use in their classroom, which can help guide students to proficiency in reading, writing, listening, and speaking in the target language. “Bryan continues to make us proud,” said UEHS Italian Teacher Amalia Roma-Circensi. “I know that this aspiring French educator will make the most out of this opportunity, and what he learns will be beneficial to his future students.” Bryan is currently at Le Moyne College, studying French and adolescent education.

Union-Endicott Central School District added 107 new photos.
June 28 at 4:08 PM ·

With a determined team of building leaders and staff, the Graduation Ceremonies of 2020 were accomplished. Even a one-day postponement due to rain and a day-of rain delay didn't stop our UEHS Class of 2020 from receiving their diplomas in-person. Divided into seven ceremonies at about 25 minutes each, students walked onto Ty Cobb Stadium, heard a live speech from Superintendent Nicole Wolfe, and then pre-recorded speeches from Daniel Vriesema, salutatorian, Alex Cass, senior class president, and Cole Rivell, valedictorian.

Following each ceremony, students and families could travel to over a dozen sites around town to get more photos. These sites included all four elementary schools, JFS middle school, and many businesses and landmarks in Endicott.

This day couldn't have been possible without the efforts and dedication of so many U-E staff, including buildings and grounds, UEHS main office and guidance staff, district and building leaders, and the board of education.

The Class of 2020 will be remembered as strong and resilient. We are #TigerPride

June 24 at 11:19 AM ·

In 2015, a group of dedicated educators decided to embark on a journey that would be known as Tiger Ventures. With the help of a substantial grant from XQ, Tiger Ventures was born and the first eighth-grade students entered the halls to learn in a way that suited their skills, their dreams, and their talents.

The program has grown over the years, in both enrollment and the business incubators that work with students on a career path. Adjustments were made, education was redesigned, recrafted, and rethought to meet individual needs while still meeting New York state graduation requirements.

And this year, a year unlike any other, Tiger Ventures celebrated its first graduating class with a small, brief ceremony in front of a limited number of family, friends, and U-E staff.

Congratulations to Ryu Luongo, Cassidy Richards, Brittany Kaczynski, and Allister Garner on being members of the Class of 2020, the very first Tiger Ventures graduates!
#TigerPride

post_text:
Throughout the last few months, so many have reached out to help our Tiger community, including both staff and businesses. One such staff member, Kashif Summers, U-E school community coordinator, looked no further than to a friend for help with food deliveries.

Over the last month Summers’ friend Dario Mass, who works for Penske Trucks, has been helping Summers with lunch deliveries. For a little over a month, they have been delivering over 100 meals to over 50 children each week. U-E school psychologist Lauri Diamantakos, who has been coordinating the grab and go lunch meal volunteer schedule, said, “This has been a huge job each week and I am so appreciative of their help!”

June 22 at 11:57 AM ·

In past years, the annual senior awards ceremony has been held in the high school auditorium in front of friends and family.

This year, as is the case with so many year-end celebrations, this one was structured a little differently. Arriving in cars, students drove up to the front of the school, got out to receive their awards, were congratulated by staff, and then had the opportunity to say a few words on the awards they received.

This year, 99 students received 301 awards, totaling more than $250,000. Thank you to all the staff who made this day possible and to all those who gave monetary donations to our graduating Tigers.

A video with our seniors sharing their awards was produced as a way to commemorate the ceremony.

Congratulations to all our seniors for their efforts in and out of the classroom. #TigerPride

They are #rhbst2020 Youth Good Samaritans sponsored by Security Mutual Life Insurance Company of New York.

You can be a hero for your community by making a donation to support the Red Cross’ mission to prevent and alleviate human suffering in the face of emergencies.

In a year like no other, students were challenged in many ways, including learning remotely. All students, K-12, were issued Chromebooks to help with online learning. For seniors, the district wanted to be sure they were prepared for what comes next and decided to gift them with the Chromebook they were issued.
All devices are part of a purchasing cycle and recycling schedule. Instead of repurposing them, seniors will get to keep them with the hopes it will help them in whatever path they choose to follow.
The district sent out information to seniors and their families on a factory reset schedule so the device will become their own personal laptop.

post_text:
Congratulations to Cole Rivell, this year’s Iron Tiger Student-Athlete.

Besides working hard and being committed to physical fitness, U-E Iron Athletes must also exemplify four principles for a positive physical culture:
-Embrace: accepting of your situation and what is to come. Know you are going to work hard.
-Relentless: continuing and persevering no matter what happens. You will finish.
-Integrity: the difference between what you say and do. Lead by example.
-Service: sacrificing for the people around you. Everything you do is for the team, school, and community.
Cole has gone above and beyond demonstrating these characteristics and managing academics and sports as this year’s class valedictorian.
#TigerPride

This year's spring season was canceled due to the pandemic. For seniors, it was especially hard to miss playing their final sport as a high school student or to be recognized on the traditional senior nights. The coaches and athletic department decided to host a senior night recognition for our 42 senior student-athletes this past Friday. Seniors arrived every five minutes to have their photo taken and receive a senior t-shirt. With masks, some took small group photos as well.

While this could never replace their season, the coaches hoped it would bring some joy to our seniors. Thank you to all who made this possible. #TigerPride #earnyourstripes

Congratulations to UEHS senior Lorenzo Carlini who is the recipient of the YES LEADs Jill Kavanagh Memorial Scholarship.

Over the past five years, Lorenzo has grown from someone who was nervous to speak in front of people into someone who thrives presenting educational information and support. He brings his positive energy into every room he enters, lifting up those around him and he goes out of his way to make students feel welcome and comfortable.

Even though the annual reception couldn’t be held this year, the group hosted a ZOOM recognition for Lorenzo with Senator Fred Akshar presenting the scholarship. Congratulations Lorenzo! #TigerPride #EarnYourStripes
shared_text:
Fred Akshar
May 21 at 6:27 AM ·

Every year, our YES Safe Choices LEADers visit hundreds of classrooms and speak to thousands of elementary students about the dangers of drugs and alcohol.

Every year we say thank you with a special reception to recognize these incredible young people. While we couldn’t make that happen this year, we’re still recognizing our most outstanding leaders through the Jill Kavanagh Memorial Scholarship.

Our first honoree is Lorenzo Carlini from Union-Endicott Central School District, a 5 year member of YES LEADs.

Over the past 5 years, Lorenzo has grown from someone who was nervous to speak in front of people into someone who thrives presenting educational information and support. He brings his positive energy into every room he enters, lifting up those around him and he goes out of his way to make students feel welcome and comfortable.

Congratulations Lorenzo!

The UEHS Business Education Department is proud to induct 13 new members into the NYS Business & Marketing Honor Society. Students selected into this society demonstrate character, leadership, and service in the classroom and through extracurricular involvement. They have met a GPA criteria and a number of business credits taken prior to graduation.

Our Class of 2020 inductees are: Muhammad Rauf Ahmad, Jacob Allen, Adielle Cano, Kentayveion Graham, Evan Hanzalik, and Zymir Mobley. (New sophomore and junior inductees will be formally inducted in the 2021 ceremony.)

post_text:
Schools may be closed for the remainder of the academic year, but that has not stopped our Tiger community from continuing the good work they do each and every day to help our families.

Members of New Life Ministries donated bags of food items for the Rotary Food Program. Derek and Caroline Waddell delivered the bags to be loaded onto the buses for delivery.

Endicott Rotary has been busy every week, shopping for food, bringing it to the district office, and helping to sort and box it for delivery.

Much of the food is purchased through generous monetary donations. Recently, OPA, ETA, UEHS School Store Club, Women's Club of Endicott, U-E Girls Tennis, and many faculty, staff, and community members donated money so Endicott Rotary can continue to provide much-needed food to our families. To date, Rotary has received $10,350 on top of $10,000 donated from the Endicott Rotary Foundation, with a total of nearly $12,450 spent so far. Endicott is an amazing community!

As both teachers and students navigate distance learning, creativity, and thinking outside the box have become even more important in the continuity of learning.

UEHS English teacher Julie Saltisiak created a fun assignment for her sophomores as part of poetry month in April. Instead of writing a basic poem on paper, she challenged them to create Book Spine Poetry, using any books, movies, or games lying around their houses. Saltisiak said, “The results were fun and I am happy with their creativity.”

It just goes to show that there are so many ways to teach and to learn!
text:
As both teachers and students navigate distance learning, creativity, and thinking outside the box have become even more important in the continuity of learning.

UEHS English teacher Julie Saltisiak created a fun assignment for her sophomores as part of poetry month in April. Instead of writing a basic poem on paper, she challenged them to create Book Spine Poetry, using any books, movies, or games lying around their houses. Saltisiak said, “The results were fun and I am happy with their creativity.”

It just goes to show that there are so many ways to teach and to learn!

post_text:
The generosity of our community knows no limits.

Janna Bickoff, who is earning her MAT in Spanish adolescent education at Binghamton University, was thinking of ways to help students and families. Bickoff spent last semester at JFS with her teacher mentor Melissa Grecco, JFS Spanish teacher.

Bickoff and two other BU students (Carolyn Johnston and Sophia Pressman) joined together in raising $500 via social media and GoFundMe in order to help students and their families. The money was used to buy black beans, pasta, chicken noodle soup, tuna, peas, carrots, and corn.

Thank you to these three BU students who showed that when we all come together, making a difference is more than possible!

post_text:
Congratulations to the UEHS Key Club on receiving the Single Service Award for its annual Holiday Party. The club also placed third in total service hours per member. The Club Single Service Award provides recognition to individual Key Clubs for their single best service project. Service hours are based on the total amount of time spent on all of the projects done throughout the year and then divided up by total members.
Adviser Theresa Brozovic said, "Our goal was achieved this year in bringing over 140 high school students, 150 elementary students, and over 100 community members together to celebrate the holiday season in a very special way. I am so proud that our members were able to organize this wonderful and altruistic event for so many of our Tiger family members. It would not be possible without the generosity of our local and school community that united to do something magical and memorable this holiday season.” #TigerPride

The yard signs were placed in yards, windows, porches or wherever most visible to show that there is a U-E Tiger senior graduating this year. Each and every senior received a sign!

The signs were purchased through Donors Choose and members of our generous community.

post_text:
"Rattle Magazine" recently asked UEHS French teacher, Susan Thornton, to read her poem, "Ghazal for Refugees," on its weekly podcast "Poets Respond." This podcast presents poems written in response to current news events. Madame Thornton's poem deals with the ongoing plight of Syrian refugees.
"Writing and the arts are very important in challenging times like these," Thornton says. "We need to express our thoughts and feelings and try to stay connected in spite of forces that would divide and weaken us." Through her experiences as a writer and educator, she asks her own students to find their voice both in and out of the classroom. Thank you for your inspiration!

Fred Akshar is with Union-Endicott Central School District.
April 17 at 5:47 PM ·

Today we also recognized 10th grader Kristopher Hodge from Union-Endicott Central School District ‘s Tiger Ventures as our latest Akshar’s All-Star for his tremendous work ethic and leadership.

Since joining Tiger Ventures, Kris became a driving force in repurposing discarded wood to construct various crafts and decorations. He then helped lead the effort in setting up a craft fair to sell his school’s creations, with the proceeds being donated to CHOW.

We may have to do things a little differently for now, but that doesn’t change the fact that our community’s outstanding students deserve to be recognized and celebrated as Akshar’s All-Stars.

UEHS senior PFC Kathleen DeLage spent a Friday morning at the district office helping to sort and package feminine hygiene products that will be delivered to U-E families.
PFC DeLage, who will be heading to the Army National Guard to study for a military career as an ICU nurse, volunteered her time along with Sgt. Marlana Watson. The products, provided by UEHS Girl Up club members Madison and Alessia Stead, were included along with food donations from Endicott Rotary.

U-E Looks to Keep Students Connected While Out of School

shared_text:
Union-Endicott Central School District added 11 new photos.
March 19 at 4:49 PM ·

Daily connection, engagement, and enrichment are vital as students, staff and educational leaders navigate this new path we are all on. With the goal of providing resources for our students so they can stay connected, engaged and enriched, the district provided a Chromebook to every K-5 Tiger. Instructions were included on how to connect so that students can contact their teachers, visit virtual classrooms, and use google docs and classrooms to work on activities, review curriculum and read. Chromebooks will be delivered to any family who was unable to come to their elementary school.

As this situation continues to unfold, we are all doing things we've not done before. The district is committed to helping in any way possible. Thank you to all who helped with distribution, traffic control, coordinating student lists, and getting the Chromebooks imaged and ready for student use.

We thank the U-E community for your patience and support. We are Tiger Strong! #TigerPride

post_text:
On day four of the county-wide school closures, U-E was a hub of activity. Our PE teachers were out and about giving away jump ropes to help keep students active.

More than 1500 backpacks of food were delivered in boxes to 136 families for the Backpack Program. The transportation department was integral in coordinating the deliveries to each and every family, with over six trips being made.

And finally, TJW staff came in and put together bags of school supplies for students to be distributed in the coming days.

We are Tiger Strong!!! #TigerPride

Union-Endicott Central School District added 18 new photos.
March 16 at 12:18 PM ·

Before schools closed, JFS held its annual World Language Week celebration.

Italian classes in collaboration with the PALS program at UEHS and JFS made homemade spaghetti, potato & ricotta gnocchi, meatballs from family recipes, homemade desserts (pizzeles, ricotta cookies, and cannoli cups), and homemade pesto and red sauce. The students also tried prosciutto with pecorino cheese, carbonated water, and espresso from Italy.

Spanish classes made homemade tortillas for sopes, homemade tamales, refried beans, empanada dough and meat filling, flan, and fresh tomato salsa.

After making all the food, students and staff sat down to share a family-style meal.

The week culminated with World Language Night, where students and their families were invited to learn more the second language opportunities the district offers, eat some great food, and enjoy crafts.

Thanks to all who made this week of learning and food possible.

This year’s JFS Science Fair was a great success with 96 participants!
Students were required to develop their projects and then present it to judges.
Eight judges from Lockheed-Martin, Binghamton University, SUNY Broome and several other community members spent the day evaluating the student projects. The winners were announced at a special evening presentation and all participants were awarded a ROAR certificate for their hard work.
The entries displayed a considerable amount of time and effort.

post_text:
It was another successful year for the Festival of Learning at GFJ with over 120 students participating.

Students in third- through fifth-grades were interviewed by district leaders and parent/community volunteers about their projects, which included a variety of topics in science, social studies, and literature. Some performed demonstrations, while others showcased their models and displays, sharing what they learned from their research.

The Festival of Learning wrapped up with a family night when families were able to view all of the student projects.

Thank you to building leaders Mary Kay Ryan and Katryn Smith, GFJ staff, district office leaders, and our many GFJ families and community members who volunteered their time, allowed us to use the gym and baked goods for this event.

Congratulations to UEHS junior Emily Amlin on receiving the Venturing Leadership Award from the Baden Powell Council, Boy Scouts of America.

This award recognizes those who have made exceptional contributions to Venturing and who exemplify the Scout Oath and Law. Emily is a member of Crew 1001 in Johnson City.

Venturing is a program for males and females aged 14-20 and Crew 1001 focuses on high-adventure outdoor activities and leadership development. Emily was instrumental in organizing and leading a council-wide Webelo’s Woods Weekend and leading activities for the 2019 Cub Adventure Weekend. #TigerPride

Troy planned and built a raised garden bed for the Church of the Holy Family to grow vegetables to be given to CHOW and to be used for church dinners that feed the needy.
Craig planned and built a storage unit for the U-E Marching Band percussion instruments. It is an organized, easily-accessible, all-weather unit for year-round storage.
#TigerPride

post_text:
AGM recently held an assembly recognizing students who displayed last month’s word, friendship, and then introduced this month’s word, perseverance.

To help kick-off the assembly, fifth-grade class president Olivia Cass invited a group of UEHS Marching Band students to perform and talk a little about how perseverance plays a role in their lives as high school students and band members. Among the students who spoke were Alex Cass (Olivia's brother and the senior class president), Natalie Klem (her mom is a teacher at AGM) and Katie McGovern (also an AGM grad and one of the drum majors).

The band marched into the assembly, taught the students a cheer that goes along with the U-E Fight Song, and played a few other tunes.

The assembly also introduced a new attendance competition between the elementary schools. School community coordinator Kashif Summers talked to the students about the importance of being in school and challenged each grade in each school to compete for the best attendance by the end of the year.
